We carried out a power spectrum analysis of the light curve using an implementation of the {\sc clean} algorithm (H\"{o}gbom 1974; Roberts, Leh\'{a}r \& Dreher 1987) by Lehto (1993). This version utilises variable gain, thereby rendering it less susceptible to falsely cleaning out a genuine periodic signal when the data are particularly noisy. The resulting power spectrum shows two distinct sets of signals (Fig.~\ref{pspec}). The first comprises a strong peak, which corresponds to a frequency of $1.5570803(1) \times 10^{-4}$~Hz along with its first harmonic. Sidebands to each, at $\pm 1$ sidereal day, remain even after moderate {\sc clean}ing.
There is a second set of frequency components with a primary period around
5.104~d, although the first harmonic at half the period is the stronger peak, and all harmonics up to $14 \times$ the fundamental frequency can be seen.


